<subSubSection id="C35CACEA7C04CA69FF21FBE32535FC82" pageId="19" pageNumber="239" type="type_taxon">
<paragraph id="8BF9FF617C04CA69FF21FBE321F8FB2F" blockId="19.[145,762,1111,1163]" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis id="B93223737C04CA69FF21FBE32146FBC8" box="[145,288,1111,1132]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">
<typeStatus id="54FD41C37C04CA69FF21FBE320A0FBC8" box="[145,198,1111,1132]" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">Type</typeStatus>
species:
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C04CA69FE9DFBE32295FBC8" authority="Boulenger, 1897" authorityName="Boulenger" authorityYear="1897" box="[301,755,1111,1133]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Lygosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="19" pageNumber="239" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="stanleyanum">
<emphasis id="B93223737C04CA69FE9DFBE32251FBC8" box="[301,567,1111,1132]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">Lygosoma stanleyanum</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFD782907C04CA69FD8DFBE32295FBC8" author="Boulenger GA" box="[573,755,1111,1133]" pageId="19" pageNumber="239" pagination="6 - 13" refId="ref43763" refString="Boulenger GA. 1897. Descriptions of new lizards and frogs from Mount Victoria, Owen Stanley Range, New Guinea, collected by Mr. A. S. Anthony. Annals and Magazine of Natural History Series 6 19: 6 - 13." type="journal article" year="1897">Boulenger, 1897</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, by original designation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF9FF617C04CA69FF21FB012286FA59" blockId="19.[145,761,1204,1901]" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis id="B93223737C04CA69FF21FB01216FFB6E" box="[145,265,1205,1226]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Medium-sized (adult SVL 
<quantity id="4CBE52847C04CA69FDFEFB002294FB6E" box="[590,754,1204,1226]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.205" metricValueMax="6.779999999999999" metricValueMin="3.63" pageId="19" pageNumber="239" unit="mm" value="52.05" valueMax="67.8" valueMin="36.3">36.3–67.8 mm</quantity>
) terrestrial skinks with short forelimbs (forelimbs 25.1– 38.9% of SVL) and moderately long hindlimbs (33.6– 49.6% of SVL); lobules present on anterior edge of ear opening; single pair of chin shields in medial contact; three supralabials posterior to subocular supralabial; chin shields abutting infralabials; lower eyelid with semitransparent window; standard three-scale temporal region; nasal scale divided by a horizontal suture extending posteriorly from the nostril; frontoparietals fused; oviparous; clutch size two; pustulate egg shells.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF9FF617C04CA69FF19F9B224ECFEBC" blockId="19.[145,761,1204,1901]" lastBlockId="19.[809,1425,197,280]" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C04CA69FF19F9B22132F9BF" authorityName="Allison &amp; Greer" authorityYear="1986" box="[169,340,1542,1563]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Papuascincus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="19" pageNumber="239" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C04CA69FF19F9B22132F9BF" box="[169,340,1542,1563]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">Papuascincus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from all other genera by having pustulate egg shells and a divided (vs. undivided) nasal scale. It further differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C04CA69FF21F9D52156F9D2" authorityName="Slavenko &amp; Tamar &amp; Tallowin &amp; Kraus &amp; Allison &amp; Carranza &amp; Meiri" authorityYear="2022" box="[145,304,1633,1654]" class="Squamata" family="Scincidae" genus="Nubeoscincus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Reptilia" pageId="19" pageNumber="239" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C04CA69FF21F9D52156F9D2" box="[145,304,1633,1654]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">Nubeoscincus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C04CA69FE8EF9D52181F9D2" authorityName="GREER" authorityYear="1974" box="[318,487,1633,1654]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Prasinohaema" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="19" pageNumber="239" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C04CA69FE8EF9D52181F9D2" box="[318,487,1633,1654]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">Prasinohaema</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C04CA69FD93F9D52218F9D2" authorityName="Greer" authorityYear="1974" box="[547,638,1633,1654]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Lobulia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="19" pageNumber="239" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C04CA69FD93F9D52218F9D2" box="[547,638,1633,1654]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">Lobulia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having one pair of chin shields in medial contact (vs. two pairs) and an oviparous (vs. viviparous) reproductive mode. It further differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C04CA69FDA3F90922D9F976" authorityName="Slavenko &amp; Tamar &amp; Tallowin &amp; Kraus &amp; Allison &amp; Carranza &amp; Meiri" authorityYear="2022" box="[531,703,1725,1746]" class="Squamata" family="Scincidae" genus="Nubeoscincus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Reptilia" pageId="19" pageNumber="239" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C04CA69FDA3F90922D9F976" box="[531,703,1725,1746]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">Nubeoscincus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C04CA69FF21F9682126F955" authorityName="GREER" authorityYear="1974" box="[145,320,1756,1777]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Prasinohaema" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="19" pageNumber="239" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C04CA69FF21F9682126F955" box="[145,320,1756,1777]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">Prasinohaema</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having the standard three-scale temporal region (vs. fragmented temporal region) and the chin shields abutting the infralabials (vs. chin shields separated from infralabials by a row of genials). It further differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C04CA69FD9AF8E322B3F8C8" authorityName="GREER" authorityYear="1974" box="[554,725,1879,1900]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Prasinohaema" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="19" pageNumber="239" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C04CA69FD9AF8E322B3F8C8" box="[554,725,1879,1900]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">Prasinohaema</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by lacking green blood serum and tissues (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD782907C04CA69FB4BFF7125E7FF7E" author="Greer AE" box="[1275,1409,197,218]" pageId="19" pageNumber="239" pagination="1 - 67" refId="ref44557" refString="Greer AE. 1974. The generic relationships of the scincid lizard genus Leiolopisma and its relatives. Australian Journal of Zoology Supplementary Series 31: 1 - 67." type="book chapter" year="1974">Greer, 1974</bibRefCitation>
), a prehensile tail with a glandular tip and basally expanded subdigital lamellae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF9FF617C04CA69FC99FEF52391FE16" blockId="19.[809,1425,321,435]" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis id="B93223737C04CA69FC99FEF5238CFEF2" box="[809,1002,321,342]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">Species included:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C04CA69FC47FEF625EBFEF2" authority="(Vogt, 1932)" baseAuthorityName="Vogt" baseAuthorityYear="1932" box="[1015,1421,321,343]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Papuascincus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="19" pageNumber="239" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="buergersi">
<emphasis id="B93223737C04CA69FC47FEF62566FEF2" box="[1015,1280,321,343]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">Papuascincus buergersi</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFD782907C04CA69FABDFEF525E5FEF2" author="Vogt T" box="[1293,1411,321,342]" pageId="19" pageNumber="239" pagination="281 - 294" refId="ref46787" refString="Vogt T. 1932. Beitrag zur Reptilienfauna der ehemaligen Kolonie Deutsch-Neuguinea. Sitzungsberichte der Gesellschaft Naturforschender Freunde zu Berlin 1932: 281 - 294." type="journal article" year="1932">Vogt, 1932</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C04CA69FC99FED4248AFED1" authority="(Parker, 1936)" baseAuthorityName="Parker" baseAuthorityYear="1936" box="[809,1260,352,374]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Papuascincus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="19" pageNumber="239" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="morokanus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C04CA69FC99FED4242EFED1" box="[809,1096,352,373]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">Papuascincus morokanus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFD782907C04CA69FBE5FED42485FED2" author="Parker HW" box="[1109,1251,352,374]" pageId="19" pageNumber="239" pagination="66 - 93" refId="ref45739" refString="Parker HW. 1936. A collection of reptiles and amphibians from the mountains of British New Guinea. Annals and Magazine of Natural History Series 10 17: 66 - 93." type="journal article" year="1936">Parker, 1936</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C04CA69FB46FED4245DFE30" authority="(Vogt, 1932)" baseAuthorityName="Vogt" baseAuthorityYear="1932" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Papuascincus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="19" pageNumber="239" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="phaeodes">
<emphasis id="B93223737C04CA69FB46FED423FFFE37" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">Papuascincus phaeodes</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFD782907C04CA69FC1DFECB2449FE37" author="Vogt T" box="[941,1071,382,404]" pageId="19" pageNumber="239" pagination="281 - 294" refId="ref46787" refString="Vogt T. 1932. Beitrag zur Reptilienfauna der ehemaligen Kolonie Deutsch-Neuguinea. Sitzungsberichte der Gesellschaft Naturforschender Freunde zu Berlin 1932: 281 - 294." type="journal article" year="1932">Vogt, 1932</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C04CA69FBFBFECB2394FE16" authority="(Boulenger, 1897)" baseAuthorityName="Boulenger" baseAuthorityYear="1897" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Papuascincus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="19" pageNumber="239" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="stanleyanus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C04CA69FBFBFECB25F7FE37" box="[1099,1425,382,404]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">Papuascincus stanleyanus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFD782907C04CA69FC81FE292381FE16" author="Boulenger GA" box="[817,999,413,435]" pageId="19" pageNumber="239" pagination="6 - 13" refId="ref43763" refString="Boulenger GA. 1897. Descriptions of new lizards and frogs from Mount Victoria, Owen Stanley Range, New Guinea, collected by Mr. A. S. Anthony. Annals and Magazine of Natural History Series 6 19: 6 - 13." type="journal article" year="1897">Boulenger, 1897</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF9FF617C04CA69FC99FE682563FDEA" blockId="19.[809,1424,478,590]" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis id="B93223737C04CA69FC99FE6823BDFE55" box="[809,987,476,497]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">D i s t r i b u t i o n:</emphasis>
M e m b e r s o f 
<emphasis id="B93223737C04CA69FB2EFE682530FE55" box="[1182,1366,476,497]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">Pa p u a s c i n c u s</emphasis>
a r e widespread across montane regions of New 
<collectingCountry id="F351BFF17C04CA69FA85FE4E25EAFDB4" box="[1333,1420,506,528]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">Guinea</collectingCountry>
, ranging from the Papuan Peninsula to the Central Highlands in 
<collectingRegion id="498231837C04CA69FC74FD8C2410FDEA" box="[964,1142,568,590]" country="Indonesia" name="Papua Barat" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">Papua Province</collectingRegion>
(
<collectingCountry id="F351BFF17C04CA69FB35FD8C249FFDEA" box="[1157,1273,568,590]" name="Indonesia" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF9FF617C04CA69FC99FDC22535FC82" blockId="19.[809,1425,630,806]" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis id="B93223737C04CA69FC99FDC223C7FD2F" box="[809,929,630,651]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">Remarks:</emphasis>
The genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C04CA69FBF3FDC32497FD28" authorityName="Allison &amp; Greer" authorityYear="1986" box="[1091,1265,631,652]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Papuascincus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="19" pageNumber="239" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C04CA69FBF3FDC32497FD28" box="[1091,1265,631,652]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">Papuascincus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
most likely contains more species than currently recognized (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD782907C04CA69FC81FD00247EFD6D" author="Slavenko A &amp; Tamar K &amp; Tallowin OJS &amp; Allison A &amp; Kraus F &amp; Carranza S &amp; Meiri S" box="[817,1048,692,714]" pageId="19" pageNumber="239" pagination="106749" refId="ref46361" refString="Slavenko A, Tamar K, Tallowin OJS, Allison A, Kraus F, Carranza S, Meiri S. 2020. Cryptic diversity and nonadaptive radiation of montane New Guinea skinks (Papuascincus; Scincidae). Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 146: 106749." type="journal article" year="2020">
Slavenko 
<emphasis id="B93223737C04CA69FC2FFD0023B0FD6D" box="[927,982,692,713]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">et al.</emphasis>
, 2020
</bibRefCitation>
). However, members of the genus appear to be more morphologically conservative than the other genera described in this manuscript. A full taxonomic revision of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4684E27C04CA69FB92FCA424DBFC81" authorityName="Allison &amp; Greer" authorityYear="1986" box="[1058,1213,784,805]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Papuascincus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="19" pageNumber="239" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93223737C04CA69FB92FCA424DBFC81" box="[1058,1213,784,805]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="239">Papuascincus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is underway.
</paragraph>
